ited States\nis no doubt. That the conditions are! was one of the allies, there is every\nthe natural outcome of the high prices probability that the other nations will\ntry to get \"George\" to do it. That\nmeans that Uncle Sam will be urged\nto put up the larger part of the am\nount.\nIt is called a loan, but every person\nthat have prevailed and the necessary\nbusiness adjustment following war,\nthere is equally no doubt.\nThe leading business men and fi\nnanciers all over the country are\ntalking hopefully of the situation and 'knows that when it is \"loaned\" it sim\ndo not hesitate to say that the bot\ntom lias been reached and that solid\nconditions may be expected not later\nthan June of this year. Business\nis even now assuming a better phaxe\nin some lines. At the same time some\nlines arc feeling increased depression,\nbut on the whole the conditions are\nimproving.\nOne of -the most favorable condi\ntions that prevail is the disposition\nshown by labor to submit to a re\nduction of wages as the price of liv\ning comes down. Any sensible per-\nson must see that the very high wages\nof the past year or two must come\ndown along with living expenses.\nLabor is seeing it and is acting with\ngood sense and reason in admitting\nthe .reduction.\nIf every business man and others J\nwill talk hopefully, make an ener\ngetic effort to continue business as\nusual, not hoard or waste, but use\ncareful judgment in all his transac\ntions and encourage the people with\nthe feeling that this is only a shad\now and will boon pass, the good and\nstable business times we all want to\nsee will come much quicker than if\nall wear gloomy faces, talk depres\nsoiu and disaster and by restricted\nbusiness help to hold with us this\nperiod of slack business.\nThis section has been more for\ntunate than many places and our\npeople should feel grateful and do all\npossible to keep up hope and confi\ndence. That will mean better con\nditions for us all and help to bring\n.us, at an earlier date, the good times\nthat are just now a short distance\naround the corner, as it were, and are\nwaiting to, be welcomed by us all..\nTalk confidence, hope and cheer\nand you will not have time nor place\nfor gloom or depression.\nply means a gift to Austria for she\nwill never pay it back for she will al\nways adopt the German subterfuge of\n\"Can't, not able.\"\nIf your Uncle Sam employs his us\nual hard sense, Austria will receive no\naid from America.\nWe are being called upon for mil\nlions to feed the starving hordes of\nPoland, the Near East and China. The\nNation- is responding nobly and will\ncontinue to do so as long as need\nrenders it necessary, but this govern\nment is not called upon to turn over\nto Austria any amount of money as a\nloan that will never be paid.\nThe census bureau has given out\nthe statement that more than half of\nthe people of continental United\nStates now live in cities of 2,500 in\nhabitants and over.\nland\nI, J. S. Reed, Cashier of the above\nnamed bank, do solemnly swear tha\nthe above statement is true to th\nbest of my knowledge and belief,\n(signed) J. S. REED.\nCashier.\nCorrect: Attest W. J. HODGES,\na M. MARTIN,\nJ. R. MITCHELL,\nDirector\nSubscribed and sworn to bctoe me\nthis nth day of January, 1921,\n(seal) 0. B. RECTOR,\nNotary Public\nWonderful, MyeUrleus Leve,\nShe was a beautiful girl, bubbling\nover, wiui intellect, an ambitious' girt,\ntoo who had studied out the matrimo\nnial problem to a nicety. \"Yes, I sup\npose 1 snail eventually wen,\" she said\n\"nut the only kind of masculine\nnuisance that will suit me must bo\ntall and dark, with classical features.\nHe must b brave, jret gentle, withal\nhe must be strong a Hon among men,\nbut a knight among ladle.\" That eve\nning a bew-lefged, lath-framed youth,\nwith red hair and bat-wing ears, wear\ning check trousers, and smoking\nclgarct that smelled worse than\nburning boot, rattled on the railings\nwith a whaaiee, and the beautiful girl\nknocked four tumblers anil a cut-glass\nfruit dish off the side-board In her\nbaste to get to him.\nWren. Ism ef Independence.\nA' shew of tndependenre Is usually\nabout as ridiculous as It Is unwise. It's\nthe exhibition f a mind that has not\nrisen to the point where it sees things\nIn perspective. Tlrel ef one thing It\ndecides that It will cut the job and do\nsomething else. But as a matter of\nfact meet people just change their de\npendence from one employer to an\nether, and every time they do It they\nare becoming more Instead of less de\npendent. Krery change of job that Is\nnot promotion Is a step backward.\nMost folks cant be made to see It\nThey cannot understand that they have\nto begin over again and that means re\nnewed dependence. Think It over be\nfore you take the next leap. Grit\nShould Senator Reed Smoot's an-ti-cigaret\nbill become a law, President-elect\nHarding will mave to cut\nout his cigaret smoking.\nThe women have been agitating con\nsiderable attempting to induce Mr.\n.Harding to drop the cigaret habit,\nbut thus far without avail. Now they\nplan to have a bill passed by congress\nprohibiting cigaret smoking.\nThcr is much probability that the\nbill will be amended to death and not\nbecome a law at this time, but the ag\nitation against the use of tobacco is\nbound to grow and not many yeears\nhence the public is likely to see some\nsuch a campaign waged againstto\n\nsucn a campaign wageu against iu\nintoxicants.\nCharter N0.9800 Reserve Dist. N0.6\nReport of Condition of the\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK,\nCrossville, Tennessee\nAt close of business, Dec. 29th, J920\nRESOURCES\nLoans and Discounts $223392.46\nOverdrafts unsecured 1,008.86\nU. S. Government Secu\nrities owned\nU. S. Bonds to secure Or\nculation 15,000.00\nU. S. Securities owned and\nand unpledged 58,850.00\nOther Bonds and Secur\nities Securities, other than U.\nS. Bonds owned and un\npledged -,500.00\nStock in Federal Reserve\nBank\nBanking House\nFurniture and Fixtures\nLawful Reserve with t